oli disease). <b>(e)</b> Caroli disease. Contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image shows saccular dilatation of the IBD and the “central dot sign” (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.263055164&amp;id=F17E">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F18A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.263055164/asset/images/g06ma15c18a.jpeg" height="882" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F18A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 18a.</b>  Uneven fatty replacement of the pancreas. <b>(a)</b> Drawings illustrate the four different patterns of fatty replacement of the pancreas (gray areas). The percentage of cases of uneven pancreatic lipomatosis represented by each type is also indicated. <b>(b)</b> CT scan shows type 1a fatty replacement of the pancreatic head (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.263055164&amp;id=F18A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F18B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.263055164/asset/images/g06ma15g18b.gif" height="315" width="440" aria-labelledby="F18B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 18b.</b>  Uneven fatty replacement of the pancreas. <b>(a)</b> Drawings illustrate the four different patterns of fatty replacement of the pancreas (gray areas). The percentage of cases of uneven pancreatic lipomatosis represented by each type is also indicated. <b>(b)</b> CT scan shows type 1a fatty replacement of the pancreatic head (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.263055164&amp;id=F18B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F19A" class="graphic"><img sr